Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 2:08 pm [sf]
Defendant Selena R Soto in court with Attorney Sylvie Dahnert. DA Susan Victoria Happ appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Constitutional rights given; plea of "Guilty" entered; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; Court finds the plea has been entered freely, voluntarily, intelligently and accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders JOC entered.

Court withholds sentence, places Defendant on Probation for 12 months, with conditions:
--follow through with all recommended mental health treatment as recommended by her providers
--Any other assessment, treatment or counseling per agent
--Take all prescribed medications as prescribed
--Maintain employment and/or education program per agent 
--No contact with Javin M. Vogel or Donovan Cagney excpet as authorized by her agent
--No acts/threats of violence towards any persons
--to pay costs of $243
--to pay $200 DNA surcharge

Court does not require defendant to provide a DNA sample.
Court requires the defendant to report to the Jefferson Probation Office today after Court.
